The anticipation of her condition during her husband's absence, deprived by his cruelty of the society of her oldest daugh- ter, forces upon the imagination of Clytaemnestra the lirst idea of that guilty conduct, which in the sequcl of the story she adopted. She therefore implores him not to drive her to such guilt, and then explains what she means in the words κακῆι γενέσθαι περὶ od, hy a threat, intimating the kind of reception which he might expect on his return to Argos.
